              and Elizabeth, who knew what curiosities his letters always were, looked over her, and read it likewise. It was as follows:

He was not seated by her;
             perhaps that was the reason of his silence; but it had not been so in Derbyshire. There he had talked to her friends, when he could not to
             herself.

The surprise of the rest of the family, on hearing who their visitor had been, was very great;
              but they obligingly satisfied it, with the same kind of supposition which had appeased Mrs. Bennet's curiosity; and Elizabeth was spared from much
